---
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";
import Footer from "$components/Footer.astro";
import Header from "$components/Header.astro";
import BaseLayout from "$layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import ProseWrapper from "$layouts/ProseWrapper.astro";
import { SITE_DESCRIPTION, SITE_TITLE } from "../../config.json";

const chapters = await getCollection("observabilitySeries");
const sorted = chapters.sort((a, b) => a.data.order - b.data.order);
const appendixChapters = sorted.filter((ch) => ch.id.startsWith("ch-99-"));
const contentChapters = sorted.filter((ch) => !ch.id.startsWith("ch-99-"));

const modules = [
	{
		number: 0,
		title: "Foundations",
		description:
			"The production framing, the telemetry structure, and the signals worth tracking first.",
	},
	{
		number: 1,
		title: "Safety, Privacy & Evaluation",
		description:
			"What not to capture, how PII leaks into telemetry, and how evaluation becomes an observability signal.",
	},
	{
		number: 2,
		title: "Security & Cost Controls",
		description:
			"Guardrail telemetry, security signals, cost attribution, budget limits, and loop controls.",
	},
	{
		number: 3,
		title: "Hands-on Implementation",
		description:
			"LangGraph, OpenTelemetry, Langfuse, LLM spans, tool spans, retrieval spans, and production hardening.",
	},
	{
		number: 4,
		title: "Operations",
		description:
			"Dashboards, alerts, and runbooks for operating AI agents day to day.",
	},
];
---

<BaseLayout
	title={`Observability for AI Agents - ${SITE_TITLE}`}
	description={SITE_DESCRIPTION}
>
	<Header active="series" />

	<main class="max-w-2xl lg:max-w-3xl mx-auto mt-8 px-4">
		<ProseWrapper>
			<h1>Observability for AI Agents in Production</h1>
			<p class="text-lg text-base-500 dark:text-base-400 italic !mt-0">
				Applying observability to agentic systems
			</p>

			<p>
				AI agents fail differently from traditional services. A request can return
				HTTP 200, finish within the latency budget, and still be wrong, unsafe, too
				expensive, or impossible to debug. Traditional APM covers infrastructure
				health. Agent observability also has to show decisions, tool calls,
				retrieval, loops, and cost.
			</p>

			<p>
				This series shows how to apply observability to production agentic systems.
				It starts with traces, spans, sessions, cost, safety, and metadata-first
				telemetry. Then it applies those ideas in a LangGraph + OpenTelemetry +
				Langfuse stack that shows what the agent did, why it did it, how much it
				cost, and where it needs attention.
			</p>

			<h3>What the series covers</h3>
			<ul>
				<li>
					A trace-first view of decisions, tool chains, retrieval, cost, and safety
					events.
				</li>
				<li>
					A metadata-over-content strategy that protects user data while preserving
					enough signal to debug production behavior.
				</li>
				<li>
					A prioritized signal list for LLM calls, tools, retrieval, sessions, loops,
					guardrails, budgets, and handoffs.
				</li>
				<li>
					A practical implementation path using LangGraph, OpenTelemetry semantic
					conventions, and Langfuse.
				</li>
				<li>
					Dashboard, alert, and runbook patterns for operating agents day to day.
				</li>
			</ul>

			<p>
				The applied chapters use Python and LangGraph. The same instrumentation
				approach can be adapted to other agent frameworks and OTLP-compatible
				backends. The aim is simple: make agent behavior auditable without turning
				your observability system into a second copy of user data.
			</p>

			<hr />

			{
				modules.map((mod) => {
					const moduleChapters = contentChapters.filter(
						(ch) => ch.data.module === mod.number,
					);
					return (
						<section>
							<h2>
								Module {String(mod.number).padStart(2, "0")} - {mod.title}
							</h2>
							<p>{mod.description}</p>
							<ul>
								{moduleChapters.map((ch) => (
									<li>
										<a href={`/observability-ai-agents/${ch.id}/`}>
											Ch {ch.data.order}: {ch.data.title}
										</a>
										<br />
										<span class="text-sm text-base-500">
											{ch.data.description}
										</span>
									</li>
								))}
							</ul>
						</section>
					);
				})
			}
			{
				appendixChapters.length > 0 && (
					<section>
						<h2>Appendix</h2>
						<ul>
							{appendixChapters.map((ch) => (
								<li>
									<a href={`/observability-ai-agents/${ch.id}/`}>
										{ch.data.title}
									</a>
									<br />
									<span class="text-sm text-base-500">
										{ch.data.description}
									</span>
								</li>
							))}
						</ul>
					</section>
				)
			}
			<hr />
			<section class="text-sm text-base-500 dark:text-base-400">
				<p>
					<strong>License & Attribution</strong><br />
					This series content is licensed under
					<a
						href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"
						target="_blank"
						rel="noopener noreferrer"
					>
						Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International (CC BY 4.0)
					</a>. You are free to share and adapt this material for any purpose,
					including commercial use, as long as you give appropriate credit.
				</p>
				<p>
					Please cite as: <em
						>"Observability for AI Agents in Production" by William Oliveira - <a
							href="https://woliveiras.com/observability-ai-agents/"
							>woliveiras.com</a
						></em
					>
				</p>
			</section>
		</ProseWrapper>
	</main>

	<Footer />
</BaseLayout>
